The paper focuses on detecting adversarial examples in deep neural networks, specifically using convolutional filter statistics. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of statistics and classification mechanisms, which are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and cryptography (cs.CR). Finally, the paper mentions the non-subdifferentiability of the resulting classifier, which is a characteristic of neural networks and optimization (cs.NE).
